         <abstract>
            <p>On June 19, 1987, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME), the New York Futures Exchange (NYFE) and the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) changed the expiration day of some index futures and select index options in an effort to reduce the impact of the triple witching hour. Since June 1987, market activity on derivative contract expiration days has not been abnormal when compared with trading on non-expiration days. However, as there had been no evidence of significant price distortions prior to the change, it is difficult to conclude that the CME changes caused a decrease in price distortions. Even so, the volatility of returns remains high during expiration periods, most likely because of the unwinding of intermarket arbitrage positions.</p>
          </abstract>
